#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:11
msgid "Foreword"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:13
msgid ""
"This book contains all the competitive scenarios for <i>Space Empires 4X,"
" Close Encounters, Replicators</i>, and <i>All Good Things</i>. The base "
"game and both previous expansions are necessary to take advantage of all "
"the options found here. These rules assume that you are using the updated"
" player aid cards provided with <i>All Good Things</i>. Cross-references "
"to sections will be included in parentheses, e.g., ([5.7]). References to"
" the Master Rule Book and the Solo/Co-Op Scenario Book will be notated "
"accordingly, e.g. ([MRB 5.5]) or ([SSB 8.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:21
msgid "Standard Rules For Competitive Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:29
msgid "Player At-Start Forces"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:31
msgid ""
"Unless otherwise specified, in each scenario each player gets the "
"following: • A fully developed 30 CP Homeworld. When playing with the "
"optional rules for Facilities ([MRB 36.0]), the 20 CP Homeworld counter "
"is used instead."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:32
msgid ""
"• Three Colony Ships, one Miner, four Shipyards (SY), and three Scouts "
"(SC) at their Homeworld."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:33
msgid "• One Flagship (optional, [MRB 23.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:41
msgid "Customizable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:43
msgid ""
"Give each rule a shot before you judge it. A lot of thought and play went"
" into them. However, once familiar with the game, feel free to play the "
"game any way you want – this game is meant to be customized. You won’t "
"offend the designer!"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:51
msgid "Galaxy Setup"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:53
msgid ""
"Unless otherwise specified, Home System markers of a player’s color are "
"placed in hexes that represent their home territory and Deep Space System"
" markers (white) are placed in all other hexes – even hexes that could "
"possibly have been a Home System area if there were more players. Excess "
"System markers are set aside."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:61
msgid "Warp Points and Doomsday Machines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:63
msgid ""
"Warp Point and Doomsday Machine counters should not be removed from the "
"game at setup. However, unless you are playing with the appropriate "
"optional rule ([MRB 28.2]; [MRB 29.0]), they are considered “open space” "
"and are removed from the game when flipped. Feel free to do this with "
"every counter players agree not to use in their game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:71
msgid "2-Player Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:73
msgid ""
"The victory condition for each scenario, unless stated otherwise, is to "
"destroy your opponent’s Homeworld. However, the winning side can often "
"become obvious before that, and it is suggested that you end the game at "
"that point."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:81
msgid "Multiplayer Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:83
msgid ""
"Victory in multiplayer games, unless stated otherwise, is to destroy one "
"opponent’s Homeworld. When any player destroys any other player’s "
"Homeworld, they become the victor."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:91
msgid "Multiplayer Short Game Victory Condition (Colony points)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:93
msgid "In addition to the condition in [1.1.6] above:"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:94
msgid ""
" • A player wins by scoring 3 Colony Points. A player gets a Colony Point"
" by:"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:95
msgid ""
"   - Destroying (not damaging) another player’s Colony. This includes new"
" Colonies, but not Colony Ships. Once gained, this Colony Point cannot be"
" lost. Capturing another player’s Colony using ground combat also counts "
"towards this requirement ([MRB 21.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:96
msgid ""
"   - By having a 5 CP Colony in Deep Space or an opponent’s Home System. "
"Unlike points earned by destroying Colonies, this Colony Point is not "
"permanent. A player has it only for so long as they have a 5 CP Colony in"
" those sections of the map."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:97
msgid ""
"   - A captured Colony may count for up to two Colony Points. Capturing "
"another player’s Colony yields 1 point. If that Colony grows to 5 CP, and"
" it is outside of the player’s Home System, it would then count as an "
"additional point (like any other Colony outside the player’s Home "
"System). The point for capturing it can never be lost, but the point for "
"having a Colony at 5 CP could be. If a player recaptures a Colony that "
"previously belonged to them it does not yield a Colony Point for "
"destroying a colony, but may yield a colony point for growing to 5 CP if "
"outside the Home System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:98
msgid ""
"• A player wins the instant they score their third Colony Point and the "
"game ends immediately, even if it is mid-turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:99
msgid ""
"• If multiple players score their third Colony Point in the same Economic"
" Phase, the win goes to the player with the most Colony Points. In the "
"event of a tie, after the purchases for the Economic Phase are completed,"
" the players add up the CP value of all combat-capable ships they have on"
" the board and the winner is the player whose fleet adds up to the most "
"CP. In the event of another tie, the tied players share the win."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:100
msgid ""
"• If playing with Variable Map setup ([3.2], [4.2]), Colony Points are "
"only scored for destroying Colonies – not for having them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:108
msgid "Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:110
msgid ""
"Players are eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. Remove all of "
"their pieces and Colonies. <i>Yes, we realize that their civilization "
"would not disappear when this happens. This represents them ceasing to "
"function as a political entity.</i> The mechanism to bring the individual"
" planets into your empire is represented by colonization. The winner is "
"the last player standing. A player that eliminates another player gets a "
"bonus 30 CPs in the next Economic Phase. If the player they conquered has"
" technology that they do not possess, they may choose one level of two "
"separate technologies from that player and mark them as researched on "
"their own sheet. Homeworlds that are re-colonized by other players act as"
" normal Colonies (they normally produce at most 5 CPs)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:118
msgid "[b]“Sinister” Victory Condition[/b]"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:120
msgid ""
"A player wins by eliminating the Homeworld of the player on their left. "
"This creates two fronts for each player (one offensive and one defensive)"
" and reduces the likelihood of two players ganging up to eliminate a "
"third. <i>The archaic definition of sinister is “related to the left side"
"/left-handed.” The notion that left- handedness was a sign of sin/evil "
"has led to the modern usage of sinister to mean so.</i>"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:128
msgid "Simultaneous Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:130
msgid "To speed up play (so that you can"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:131
msgid ""
"play more games!), many parts of Space Empires were designed to be done "
"simultaneously. Much of the early turns can be done simultaneously. When "
"playing with experienced players, it is suggested (if there is no threat "
"of direct interaction) that all players conduct their turns at once and "
"only wait for people in order to keep everyone in the same Economic "
"Phase. It is recommended to switch to sequential turns at the latest when"
" only two rows of deep space remain unexplored between players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:139
msgid "Quick Start Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:141
msgid "Use this suggestion for quicker"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:142
msgid ""
"play. After setting up, flip all Home System markers and place a full-"
"strength Colony on all non-barren planets. In this scenario, the players "
"do not start with any Colony Ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:150
msgid "(Small) Handicap Rule"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:152
msgid "Use this rule to provide a"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:153
msgid ""
"small advantage to a less-experienced player by increasing their CP "
"income during the early game. During each Economic Phase, the income of "
"that player’s Colonies will increase by two steps. For example, a Colony "
"Ship is flipped to its Colony side and a “3 Colony” marker is placed on "
"top instead of a “1 Colony.”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:161
msgid "Variable but Balanced Home Systems"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:163
msgid "In this"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:164
msgid ""
"variant, all players have the same markers in their Home Systems, but no "
"player is aware of which markers are in play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:165
msgid ""
"• All players set aside the following markers from their Home Systems: "
"two non-barren Planets, two 5-Mineral counters, one Asteroid, and one "
"Nebula."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:166
msgid ""
"• Each player then also sets aside all 8 of the new Home System markers "
"(these are marked with a “v” on the front side): one Supernova, one Fold "
"in Space, two 10-Mineral counters, one Space Wreck, one Space Pirate, and"
" two 10 CP Planets (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:167
msgid ""
"• All these counters are organized into stacks of one counter of each "
"type per player. This will create 14 stacks. EXAMPLE: In a 3-player game,"
" there will be 14 stacks of 3 counters each – one from each player: One "
"stack with one Asteroids from each player; two stacks with one 10-Mineral"
" counter from each player, etc."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:168
msgid ""
"• Players collectively choose 6 of the 14 stacks. These stacks should be "
"chosen randomly and blindly so all players are unaware of which markers "
"will be included in the game. Each player takes their 6 markers and "
"shuffles them back into their Home System markers before setting up their"
" Home System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:169
msgid ""
"10 CP Planets will grow to 5 CP like any other Colony and will then grow "
"to 10 CP the following phase. At 5 CP, place a flipped Colony Ship on "
"top; remove it when the Colony reaches 10 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:177
msgid "Gameplay Advice"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:179
msgid ""
"The play time for this game is in the 1 to 4-hour range for a 2-player "
"game, depending on the scenario. For multiplayer games, the play time "
"will be at the higher end of that range. Since new players tend to take "
"longer the first couple of times they play any game, here are some "
"suggestions to keep play time down in the early games."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:180
msgid ""
"• Start with just the basic rules. While they are fairly simple, the game"
" offers a lot of choices and decisions. Starting with just the basic "
"rules simplifies some of the choices and makes the first few Economic "
"Phases easier to wrap your head around."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:181
msgid ""
"• Start with the Small 2-Player Scenario. This is a scenario that "
"experienced players can finish in less than an hour and a half. Even if "
"it takes a new player an hour longer than that, it is easily manageable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:182
msgid ""
"• For the first multiplayer game, play teams. It will drastically shorten"
" the playing time as you are learning the game. Try to pair an "
"experienced player with a beginner if possible."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:183
msgid "• Be aggressive! This is a game that rewards aggressive play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:191
msgid "Player Alliances"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:193
msgid ""
"Some 3-Player or 4-Player scenarios include rules called UNEASY ALLIANCE "
"or BLOOD BROTHERS. When using either of these rules in any scenario, "
"teammates win or lose the game together. Also, you may not capture "
"Colonies from your allies with Ground Units ([MRB 21.0]) nor may you use "
"Boarding Ships ([MRB 19.0]) on your allies. You may never bombard "
"Colonies that your allies originally colonized."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:201
msgid "Uneasy Alliance"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:203
msgid "Teammates may never stack units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:204
msgid "of any kind in the same hex and may not use each other’s MS Pipelines."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:212
msgid "Blood Brothers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:214
msgid "Teammates execute their turns at the"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:215
msgid ""
"same time, may stack together, may attack together, and may use each "
"other’s MS Pipelines for movement. However, they may not share research "
"or CPs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:223
msgid "Definitions For All Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:225
msgid ""
"• Homeworld setup: Unless otherwise noted in the scenario rules, "
"Homeworlds may be placed in a player’s Home System hex marked with a red "
"“H” or a red-dashed line."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:226
msgid "• Hexes outside of the playing area are NOT playable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:234
msgid "2-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:243
msgid "2-Player Small"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:245
msgid ""
"• This game is good for introducing players to the system. It is also "
"good for experienced players when they have a time constraint."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:246
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:247
msgid ""
"• There are 17 Deep Space markers. • There are 26 Home System markers on "
"each side. This means that Player 2 must choose one of the half-hexes on "
"the right edge of their playing area within their Home System. This half-"
"hex gets one of the System markers and is fully playable during the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:255
msgid "2-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:257
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below). • There are 34 Deep Space markers. • There are 26"
" Home System markers on each side. This means that"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:258
msgid ""
"Player 1 must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their "
"playing area within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the "
"System markers and is fully playable during the game. • It is recommended"
" that you use Non-Player Aliens ([MRB 18.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:266
msgid "2-Player Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:268
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below). • There are 51 Deep Space markers. • There are 26"
" Home System markers on each side. This means that Player 2 must choose "
"one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their playing area within "
"their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers and is "
"fully playable during the game. • Yeah, you might want to research "
"Exploration technology…"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:276
msgid "2-Player Extra Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:278
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game. • There are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:286
msgid "2-Player “3D”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:288
msgid ""
"The title of this scenario promises more than it gives, but you’ll see "
"what we mean. • Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one "
"of the regions normally used in a 4-Player game. • There are 46 Deep "
"Space markers. • The two unused home regions get no System markers – they"
" are not in play. • More than not being in play, the unused home regions "
"need to be thought of as not being there. A player may move a ship into "
"an unused home region and come out in any other hex adjacent to that "
"unused home region. In essence, it is as if all the hexes adjacent to an "
"unused home region are adjacent to each other. • This is an attempt to "
"introduce a 3D element to the game board. Yes, it’s crude. Yes, it’s "
"simple. But we think it’s clever. ☺"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:296
msgid "2-Player Massive"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:298
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up. •"
" Player 1 will have one Home System marker and Player 2 will have six "
"Home System markers that do not fit within the area indicated by the "
"line. These should be placed in any hex adjacent to that area. • There "
"are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:306
msgid "“I Dare You To Play This”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:308
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up. •"
" The first two rows closest to each player will be filled by 25 of their "
"Home System markers. The remaining marker should be placed in any hex "
"adjacent to that area. • There are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:316
msgid "2-Player Double Trouble"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:318
msgid ""
"• Each player uses all the pieces of their color, plus the Home System "
"markers of another color. One non-Barren planet and the Homeworld is "
"removed from each player’s additional color. • The Home System markers of"
" both colors are mixed together, and each player sets up these 50 Home "
"System markers as suggested by the diagram. There are no guides on the "
"game board to indicate this set up. • The first four rows closest to each"
" player will be filled by their 50 Home System markers. • There are 50 "
"Deep Space markers. • Each player can use the Colony counters of either "
"of their colors."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:326
msgid "2-Player Knife Fight"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:328
msgid ""
"• Setup: All 26 Home System markers are used for both players. However, "
"no Deep Space markers are used. One player sets up their Home System "
"markers in one of the four quadrants used in the 4-Player game ([4.0]). "
"The other player sets up their markers in quadrant fashion, but adjacent "
"to the first player’s quadrant with no Deep Space markers between them. "
"Each player places their Homeworlds in a hex marked with an “H” in the "
"diagram above. • Starting Ships: Both players start with four SCs and "
"four Colony Ships instead of three of each. Other starting units remain "
"as per [1.1.1]. • Starting Tech: Both players start the game with Ship "
"Size 2, Ship Size 3, and Move 2 already researched."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:336
msgid "2-Player Galactic Capitol"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:338
msgid ""
"• A 2-player game with five rows of Deep Space in between and the "
"Galactic Capitol in the center hex labeled “GC” ([MRB 28.1]) • Including "
"the Galactic Capitol there are a total of 43 Deep Space markers. • There "
"are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that both players "
"must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their playing area"
" within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers "
"and is fully playable during the game. • This map can also be played "
"without the Galactic Capitol."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:346
msgid "2-Player – Single Talon Map"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:348
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the opposite "
"sides of the board as shown. • There are 118 Deep Space markers. • "
"Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:356
msgid "2-Player – Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:358
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also available through GMT Games. The two boards are placed as above, "
"with two Empires set up on the opposite sides of the map as shown. Each "
"player’s Homeworld is placed in a hex marked with an “H”. Since there are"
" 30 Home System hexes, each player will have to use 4 of the new Home "
"System markers (marked with a “v” on the front side) at random. • There "
"are 198 Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:366
msgid "2-Player – “The Belt” (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:375
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:417
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:749
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:920
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1199
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1277
msgid "Setup"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:377
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the "
"opposite sides of the board as shown. Each player’s Homeworld is placed "
"in a hex marked with an “H.” The Home System markers from a different "
"Empire are placed in the red belt between the two Empires. Remove the "
"Homeworld, one non-Barren Planet, one Asteroid counter, and one Nebula "
"before mixing them. • There are 96 Deep Space markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:385
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:428
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:797
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:930
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1363
msgid "Special Rules"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:387
msgid ""
"• Partial hexes are not used. • Do not play with the <span class=\"text-"
"uppercase\">Amazing Diplomats [g][#48][/g]</span> Empire Advantage. • "
"Non-Player Aliens are on all Deep Space and Belt planets, including those"
" that are not Barren. It is possible that you will run out of NPAs in "
"this scenario. If that happens, use a spare counter to mark which planets"
" still have NPAs and how many and draw specific ships when they are "
"attacked."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:388
msgid ""
"• All planets in Deep Space and the Belt give an Alien Technology Card "
"when colonized ([MRB 11.0]). If you run out of Alien Technology Cards, "
"reshuffle the discards to form a new draw pile. • It is recommended that "
"Doomsday Machines ([MRB 29.0]) and Warp Points ([MRB 28.2]) are NOT used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:396
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1311
msgid "Victory Conditions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:398
msgid "In addition to the normal victory"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:399
msgid ""
"conditions, a player can also win by having a Colony on six of the belt "
"planets."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:400
msgid ""
"Design Note: This is a longer game, not only because of the size of the "
"map, but because any new Colonies in the belt will be vulnerable. It will"
" be harder for one side to take a dominating lead and both sides should "
"end up deeper in the tech tree."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:408
msgid "2-Player – “Belt And Void” (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:419
msgid "Everything is the same as The Belt scenario, except"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:420
msgid ""
"that the Deep Space hexes are referred to as the “Void.” Add Deep Space "
"markers to every hex of the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:430
msgid ""
"• In the Void, (but not the Belt hexes), there are strange radiation and "
"spatial properties that make it difficult for certain ships to enter. • "
"Only Decoys, Minesweepers, Scouts, Destroyers, Raiders, Miners, "
"Transports, Titans, and any advanced versions of those ships may enter "
"the Void. • Fighters and Ground Units that are carried by one of the "
"above vessels (or on a Colony) are also allowed. • Space Pirates are "
"allowed but captured Non-Player Alien ships are not allowed to move in "
"the Void. • Bases and Shipyards can be built at Colonies in the Void and "
"can move in the Void if using the <span class=\"text-uppercase\">On the "
"Move [g][#58][/g]</span> Empire Advantage. • It is not recommended that "
"this scenario be played with Replicators. Design Note: Taking a planet "
"and establishing SYs in the belt to build bigger ships is the key to the "
"game. Ground Units will need to be used since Colony Ships cannot enter "
"the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:438
msgid "3-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:447
msgid "3-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:449
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 3-Player game (denoted by the shading on the game "
"board). • The rest of the map (including the two hexes “behind” Player 2 "
"and Player 3) gets Deep Space markers. This will use 72 of them. • If all"
" players agree, players may place their Homeworlds in any hex of their "
"Home System. Otherwise, they use the hex marked with an “H”."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:457
msgid "3-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:459
msgid ""
"• Each player takes their Homeworld and places it randomly. A 20-sided "
"die can be used for this. If one is not available, then pieces of paper "
"numbered 1 to 13 can be drawn out of a cup. The first number rolled/drawn"
" is the row in which your Homeworld will be placed and the second number "
"rolled/ drawn is the number of hexes counted over in that row. If a "
"number is rolled that is out of range, then the die is re-rolled until "
"one in range is achieved. • All other System markers, both Home System "
"and Deep Space, are mixed together and randomly placed all over the map. "
"• This will often lead to unbalanced map layouts. However, for those that"
" love diplomacy, this is all part of the challenge. Those that have "
"weaker positions often gang up on the strong."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:467
msgid "3-Player Teams – 2 Vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:469
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the 3-Player Standard scenario ([3.1]). • Mutually"
" agree or determine randomly which two players will be on the same team "
"versus the third player. • The two teammates operate under an UNEASY "
"ALLIANCE ([1.3.1]). • A player is eliminated when their Homeworld is "
"destroyed. The team wins as soon as they destroy the Homeworld of the "
"single player. The single player must eliminate both of the other players"
" in order to win. However, the single player does not get the 30 CP "
"conquering bonus listed in the Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition "
"([1.1.8]). • Each of the allied players collect income normally, but all "
"of their ships and technology cost 1.5 times normal (after applying any "
"modifiers from e.g. Alien Technology Cards ([MRB 11.0]), round up). For "
"example, a Scout would cost 9 instead of 6, a Destroyer would cost 14 "
"instead of 9, and Tactics 1 Technology would cost 23 instead of 15. • "
"Maintenance and turn order bid would still be normal cost."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:477
msgid "3-Player Teams – 2 Vs 1 With Empire"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:479
msgid ""
"ADVANTAGES The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in"
" the 3-Player Teams – 2 vs 1 scenario ([3.3]), with the following "
"exceptions: • The team of two players pays the normal cost in CP for "
"everything. They do not have to pay 1.5 times the normal amount. • The "
"team of two players does not get any Empire Advantages ([MRB 10.0]), but "
"the single player draws six Empire Advantages and gets to choose four of "
"them. As normal, these Empire Advantages remain secret until used in such"
" a way that they would be revealed or a Colony is invaded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:487
msgid "3-Player Teams - 2 Vs 1 With"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:489
msgid ""
"REPLICATORS • Setup is the same as the 3-Player Teams - 2 vs 1 scenario "
"([3.3]). • Mutually agree or determine trandomly which two players will "
"be on the same team versus the third player. • The two teammates operate "
"under an UNEASY ALLIANCE ([1.3.1]). • In this game the Replicator’s "
"Colonies start at 1 CP instead of Start. They can still be bombarded back"
" down to Start and will then grow to 1 CP – 3 CP – Full. • A player is "
"eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. The team wins as soon as "
"they destroy the Replicator player’s Homeworld. The Replicator player "
"must eliminate both of the other players in order to win. However, the "
"Replicator player does not get the 30 CP conquering bonus listed in the "
"Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition ([1.1.8].)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:497
msgid "4-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:506
msgid "4-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:508
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game (denoted by the outlined sections on the"
" game board). • The rest of the map gets Deep Space markers. This will "
"use 46 of them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:516
msgid "4-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:518
msgid "• Setup is the same as the Variable 3-Player Map ([3.2])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:526
msgid "4-Player Team Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:528
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the Standard 4-Player Map ([4.1]). • Mutually "
"agree or determine randomly what the teams will be. • Teammates can be "
"diagonally across from each other or next to one another depending on "
"personal preference. • Players must decide to play as an UNEASY ALLIANCE "
"or as BLOOD BROTHERS ([1.3])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:536
msgid "4-Player Teams With Empire"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:538
msgid ""
"ADVANTAGES • Setup is the same as 4-Player Team Play ([4.3]). • All "
"players draw Empire Advantages as per either normal method ([MRB 10.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:546
msgid "4-Player Teams – 3 Vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:548
msgid ""
"The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in the "
"4-Player Team Play scenario ([4.3]), with the following exceptions: • "
"Instead of 2 vs 2, this scenario is 3 vs 1. • The three players that are "
"on the same team are operating as BLOOD BROTHERS ([1.3.2]). • The player "
"on their own receives double the normal CP income from all Colonies "
"except their Homeworld. Example: If a player has a 30 CP Homeworld, two 3"
" CP Colonies, one of which was"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:549
msgid "connected by an MS Pipeline, the player would get 43 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:550
msgid ""
"• The single player draws three Empire Advantages ([MRB 10.0]) and picks "
"one. The three-player team draws a pool of five Empire Advantages and "
"each player will get to pick one of them. • Each of the players on the "
"three-player team starts with the technologies Terraforming 1 and "
"Scanners 1. • The single player must destroy all three of the enemy "
"Homeworlds."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:551
msgid "Design Note: This has the possibility of becoming a long scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:559
msgid "4-Player Teams - 3 Vs 1 With"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:561
msgid ""
"REPLICATORS The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given "
"in the 4-Player Teams – 3 vs 1 scenario ([4.5]), with the following "
"exceptions: • The Replicator player must be on the team with 3 players. •"
" The Replicator player draws two Empire Advantages ([MRB 10.0]) and keeps"
" one while the other two players on their team draw three Empire "
"Advantages total and each keep one."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:569
msgid "4-Player Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:571
msgid ""
"• There are 14 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, five planets, one "
"Barren Planet, and seven Mineral counters. • Each player places their "
"Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” and their remaining 13 Home System "
"markers are mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:572
msgid "• There are 94 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:580
msgid "4-Player Three Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:582
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the diagram above. • The "
"remaining 24 Home System markers for each player are mixed and placed "
"within the boundaries shown in the diagram. • The row of hexes at the "
"bottom of the map do not get markers and are not used. • There are 38 "
"Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:590
msgid "4-Player Four Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:592
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the diagram above. • The "
"remaining 24 Home System markers for each player are"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:593
msgid ""
"mixed and placed within the boundaries on the map. • There are 50 Deep "
"Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:601
msgid "4-Player Two Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:603
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires two copies of Space Empires 4X and is played on "
"two boards. Twelve blank hex tiles are used to connect the two boards on "
"their long edges. If terrain is revealed during the game in one of the "
"blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed and replaced with the "
"appropriate Terrain tile ([MRB 6.10]). • Each player places their "
"Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H”. Since there are 31 Home System "
"hexes, each player will have to use 5 of the new Home system markers "
"(marked with a “v” on the front side) at random. • There are 188 Deep "
"Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:611
msgid "4-Player Two Maps – Corners"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:613
msgid ""
"• Setup is a slightly modified version of the 4-Player Two Maps scenario "
"([4.10]) - only add 4 new Home system markers instead of 5."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:621
msgid "4-Player Large (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:623
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Each player’s Homeworld is "
"placed in a hex marked with an “H.” The remaining 25 Home System markers "
"for each player are mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the "
"diagram above. • The rest of the hexes get Deep Space markers. This will "
"use 66 of them. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:631
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps (Long Edge)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:633
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. The two boards are arranged "
"as above. Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” "
"then the remaining 25 Home System markers for each player are mixed and "
"placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 154 "
"Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:641
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps (SHORT EDGE)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:643
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:653
msgid ""
"• Setup is a slightly modified version of the 4-Player – Both Talon Maps "
"(Long Edge) scenario ([4.13])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:651
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps (With Gaps)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:661
msgid "5-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:670
msgid "5-Player Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:672
msgid ""
"• There are 11 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, five planets, and "
"five Mineral counters. • A Replicator player uses their Homeworld, four "
"planets, one Barren planet, four 10-Mineral counters and one 5-Mineral "
"counter. • Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H”"
" then the remaining ten System markers are mixed and placed within two "
"hexes of the Homeworld. Some players will have a Deep Space marker within"
" 2 hexes of their Homeworld, they may choose which hex this is. • There "
"are 95 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:680
msgid "5-Player Tight"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:682
msgid ""
"• This uses the same map as the 5-Player Deep Space scenario ([5.1]). • "
"There are 19 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, eight planets, one "
"Asteroid, one Nebula, and eight Mineral counters. • A Replicator player "
"uses their Homeworld, seven planets, one Barren planet, two Asteroids, "
"two Nebulae, four 10-Mineral counters, and two 5-Mineral counters. • Each"
" player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the "
"remaining 18 System markers are mixed and placed within three hexes of "
"the Homeworld. • There are 55 Deep Space markers. When setting up this "
"map, at least one hex of Deep Space must be between each player’s Home "
"System hexes. • There may be a turn or two where you will need to use "
"spare numeral markers to keep track of the Colony growth for all five "
"players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:690
msgid "5-Player - 3 Vs 2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:692
msgid ""
"• Use the same map and setup as the 5-Player Tight scenario ([5.2]). • "
"The Replicator Player must be part of the 3-player side. • The 3-Player "
"side draws no Empire Advantages ([MRB 10.0]). • The 2-Player team draws "
"six Empire Advantages and decides together which four they will use. Each"
" player gets the benefit of only two of the cards. • Both teams operate "
"as an UNEASY ALLIANCE ([1.3.1])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:700
msgid "6-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:709
msgid "6-Player Two Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:711
msgid ""
"• There are 21 Home System markers used by each player, except player 5, "
"which only uses 20 Home System markers. • From their Home System markers,"
" each player removes two 5-Minerals, one non-barren planet, one Asteroid,"
" and one Nebula. Player 5 removes two Asteroids instead of one. • Each "
"player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the "
"remaining 20 Home System markers (19 for player 5) for each player are "
"mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • "
"There are 25 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:719
msgid "6-Player Two Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:721
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires two copies of Space Empires 4X and is played on "
"two boards. Twelve blank hex tiles are used to connect the two boards on "
"their long edges. If terrain is revealed during the game in one of the "
"blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed and replaced with the "
"appropriate Terrain tile ([MRB 6.10]). • Twelve blank hex tiles are used "
"to connect the two boards on their long edges. If terrain is revealed "
"during the game in one of the blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed"
" and replaced with the appropriate Terrain tile ([MRB 6.10]). • Each "
"player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the "
"remaining Home System markers for each player are mixed and placed within"
" the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 156 Deep Space "
"markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:729
msgid "6-Player – Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:731
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also separately available through GMT Games. The two boards are arranged "
"as above, with each player’s Homeworld placed in a hex marked with an "
"“H.” The remaining 25 Home System markers for each player are mixed and "
"placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 102 "
"Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:739
msgid "Quick Conquest Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:741
msgid ""
"Although the Multiplayer Short Game Victory Condition (using Colony "
"Points, 1.1.7) has been popular for providing a shorter, non-team "
"multiplayer game, the point of this game has always been conquest. These "
"scenarios are meant to provide a quicker multiplayer game with conquest "
"as the victory condition."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:751
msgid ""
"• Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the "
"diagrams below. • No Mines or Minesweepers may be researched or used. • "
"Use the 30 CP Homeworld counters. • Use the <span class=\"text-"
"uppercase\">Technology Head Start [g][#148][/g]</span> Scenario Card (see"
" the Card Manifest) in addition to any other Scenario Cards. • The first "
"player to destroy a Homeworld is the winner. • These scenarios can also "
"be played with teams."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:759
msgid "3-Player Quick Conquest (Refer To [3.1])"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:768
msgid "4-Player Quick Conquest (Refer To [4.1])"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:777
msgid "Epic Scenarios for 2-8 Players"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:779
msgid ""
"• These scenarios require two copies of the game and are played on two "
"boards (see [4.10] for how to lay out two boards). • These are meant to "
"enable a game with more than four players, but any of the scenario setups"
" can be used for an epic scenario. The possibilities are numerous. - If "
"six players are in the game, using the 3-Player Standard setup on both "
"boards makes sense. - With seven players, using the 3-Player Standard "
"setup on one board and the 4-Player Standard setup on the other would "
"work. - A 2-Player game can be played where each player controls an "
"empire on both maps. - A 4-Player game could be played with two players "
"on each map using the “I Dare You to Play This” setup. In this case, it "
"is recommended that each player use all the Colony Ships of their own "
"color from both games. - An 8-Player game could be played with a Variable"
" Map setup ([3.2] or [4.2]). • If more than four players are playing, "
"then some of the same color playing pieces would have to be used. For "
"example, there might be two green empires. Empires of the same color "
"should be differentiated by starting the game on separate maps. When a "
"unit crosses over maps, it should be marked with a spare token of some "
"sort, e.g., a counter from some other game. • In an epic scenario, when "
"one player conquers another, they add all the conquered player’s pieces "
"to their build pool. • Warp Points: Warp Points ([MRB 28.2]) are the "
"connection between the boards. All six Warp Point 1s (three on each "
"board) are considered connected. The same with all six Warp Point 2s. "
"Players should agree on the number of Warp Points used on each map (i.e. "
"whether they want to discard the third warp point of each number as usual"
" or keep them in play). Deep Space markers should be mixed so that the "
"same number of Warp Points of the same ID (1 or 2) are on each map."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:787
msgid "Planetary Gate Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:789
msgid "Planetary Gate scenarios are for those who can’t get enough ground combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:806
msgid "Planetary Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:808
msgid "Each planet is"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:809
msgid ""
"connected to any other planet within three hexes by means of a Planetary "
"Gate. Ground Units ([MRB 21.0]) on one planet may move to any other "
"planet within three hexes via this Planetary Gate. That is considered "
"their entire move that turn. The <span class=\"text-uppercase\">Air "
"Support [g][#25][/g]</span> Alien Technology card does not enable "
"Transports to use Planetary Gates. Colonies built on asteroids by the "
"<span class=\"text-uppercase\">Industrious Race [g][#35][/g]</span> are "
"not connected by Planetary Gates."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:817
msgid "Barren Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:819
msgid "Barren Planets may be pre-placed in"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:820
msgid ""
"Deep Space between Home Systems so that it increases the likelihood that "
"players are connected by Planetary Gates. In the diagrams below, Barren "
"planets are placed on the hexes marked with a “B.” These are suggestions "
"for the 2-Player, 3-Player, and 4-Player game. However, players should "
"feel free to play without pre-placement of planets or come up with some "
"other mutually agreed upon layout. Players may also decide to remove all "
"Barren Planets from the remaining Deep Space System markers to limit "
"extra connectivity."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:828
msgid "Combat through Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:830
msgid "If Ground Units are moved by a"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:831
msgid ""
"Planetary Gate and the destination planet is colonized by another player "
"or Non-Player Aliens ([MRB 18.0]), ground combat occurs normally. "
"Regardless of the ground combat technology of the invading player, "
"attacking units do not get to attack in the first round. The invasion and"
" the result are handled the same as if the planet was invaded from space."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:839
msgid "Retreats"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:841
msgid "Ground Units may retreat through gates, but"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:842
msgid ""
"only to friendly planets within three hexes that are free of enemy units."
" They may retreat before bombardment or during ground combat when it is "
"their turn to fire, but not during the first round. Fighters may not "
"retreat via Planetary Gates."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:850
msgid "Alien Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:852
msgid "An NPA planet may be captured by"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:853
msgid ""
"invading through a Planetary Gate. In that case, any alien ships still in"
" orbit are removed from the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:861
msgid "Gates and Fighters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:863
msgid "Fighters ([MRB 15.2]) may move between"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:864
msgid "planets like Ground Units, but only between friendly Colonies."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:872
msgid "Colony Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:874
msgid "When a Colony Ship is purchased, it may"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:875
msgid ""
"be purchased as a non-spacefaring Colony Ship. It still costs the same, "
"but it can be placed, without the use of a Shipyard, on any Colony that "
"produced 5 CP in that Economic Phase. It should be placed ship-side-up on"
" top of the existing Colony. A non-spacefaring Colony Ship can never move"
" into space but may travel though gates like Ground Units. It must "
"colonize the first uncolonized planet that it moves to. The ship is left "
"on the uncolonized planet and is flipped in the Economic Phase just as it"
" would be if it was a normal Colony Ship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:876
msgid ""
"Similar to space combat, the CO may enter a hex with enemy units only "
"when accompanied by friendly ground units, may not retreat, and is "
"destroyed if the enemy wins the combat. Design Note:Just when you think "
"you don’t need ships anymore, that fleet shows up and starts wasting your"
" Colonies from space. Then when you let your guard down on the ground, an"
" invasion force shows up in your Home System and starts spreading from "
"planet to planet."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:884
msgid "2-Player Planetary Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:893
msgid "3-Player Planetary Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:902
msgid "4-Player Planetary Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:910
msgid "Space Amoeba Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:912
msgid ""
"Giant Space Amoebas can be added to many of the competitive scenarios in "
"this book. During the game, the Space Amoebas will multiply and attempt "
"to destroy the human players. There are similar rules for Space Amoebas "
"included in the Solo/Co-op Scenario Book ([SSB 3.0])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:922
msgid ""
"• Space Amoebas may be pre-placed in Deep Space between the Home Systems."
" No Deep Space marker is placed in a hex with an Amoeba. • In the "
"diagrams to follow, Space Amoebas are placed on the hexes marked with an "
"“S” as suggestions for the Large 2-Player Map as well as the Standard "
"3-Player and 4-Player Maps. However, players should feel free to play "
"with some other mutually agreed upon layout. • All Space Amoebas are of "
"one type (unless the players agree upon some layout with multiple types)."
" A Space Amoeba counter of any of the three included types may be used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:932
msgid ""
"• Unlike the solitary Space Amoeba scenario there are no rule "
"restrictions (i.e., Titans, Ground Combat, Facilities, etc. can be used)."
" • Unlike the solitary Space Amoeba scenario players must pay maintenance"
" as usual. • Unlike the solitary Space Amoeba scenario Barren Planets do "
"have Non-Player Aliens ([MRB 18.0]) on them. • Like in the solitaire "
"Space Amoeba scenario, Minesweepers (SW) represent Science Vessels (SV), "
"which are needed to defeat the Amoebas. However, Minesweepers pull double"
" duty in the competitive scenario. Minesweeper technology now also counts"
" as Science and must be researched to produce hybrid Minesweeper/Science "
"Vessels. A Minesweeper counter may both research Amoebas and sweep"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:933
msgid ""
"Mines. Use the costs for Minesweeper ships and Minesweeper technology for"
" producing these hybrid ships. • Only the first two levels of Minesweeper"
" technology count as Science technology. Minesweeper 3 technology may be "
"researched and used as normal, but it does not provide any additional "
"bonus to researching Space Amoebas. • If a player is eliminated by an "
"Amoeba, play continues for the remaining players until only one remains "
"(the winner) or until a victory condition is met."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:934
msgid ""
"Design Note: Yes, I know it says SW on the counters, but in this "
"scenario, it is also as if they say SV, as in Science Vessels. Pretend "
"that the SW was put on the counter by someone who heard the words "
"“Science Vessel” spoken by someone with a bad TV Russian accent (I’m "
"looking at you, Chekov)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:942
msgid "Researching Space Amoebas"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:944
msgid ""
"• Until a player has researched the Amoebas, they cannot be attacked and "
"will destroy all that player’s ships (except SVs) in the same hex. If SVs"
" are present, they may research the Amoeba before it destroys the other "
"ships. Once that player’s SVs gather 10 or more Research Points, their "
"other ships will not be automatically destroyed. • Unlike the solitaire "
"scenario, a player is not required to lose a ship to an Amoeba before "
"researching them. • Each player must research the Space Amoebas "
"individually. • Research Points carry over from turn to turn, and each "
"player should track their own research completion. • As soon as an SV is "
"in the same hex with an Amoeba, one or more dice are rolled for each SV "
"to represent that ship’s research into the Amoebas. - 1-2: Two Research "
"Points gained. - 3-5: One Research Point gained. - 6-8: Nothing. - 9-10: "
"SV destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:945
msgid ""
"• Level 1 Science Vessels roll one die when researching. • Level 2 "
"Science Vessels get to roll two dice and use the best result. • Level 2 "
"Science/Minesweeper technology can’t be acquired until a Level 1 Science "
"Vessel has researched an Amoeba (successful or not). • Once a player has "
"a total of 10 Research Points, that player may attack any Amoeba they "
"encounter for the rest of the game. • A Science Vessel may research an "
"Amoeba on the same turn the ship moves into its hex. • Multiple SVs can "
"research each turn they are in a hex with an Amoeba. • If an SV shares a "
"hex with any Amoeba after they are completely researched, that ship still"
" must roll a die for research as normal and may be destroyed on a roll of"
" 9-10. No further Research Points are gained. • After 10 Research Points "
"have been gathered by a player, the Amoebas will no longer automatically "
"destroy their ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:946
msgid ""
"Instead, combat ensues as normal. However, Science Vessels never "
"participate in combat with an Amoeba."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:954
msgid "Space Amoeba Strength"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:956
msgid ""
"After a player has gathered 10 Research Points, it means they have "
"figured out how to kill the Amoebas. Design Note: In sci-fi terms, the "
"Amoeba can be killed if the player slightly tweaks their weapons – by "
"adjusting the frequency to the upper EM band, by adjusting the phase, by "
"reversing the polarity, or by doing something else pseudo-scientific "
"sounding. The specific adjustment is not important. It means it is now "
"possible to (immediately) attack them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:957
msgid ""
"No retrofit (technology upgrade) is needed for ships in order to attack "
"([MRB 9.11.3])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:965
msgid "Determine Amoeba Strength"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:967
msgid ""
"• The first player to gather 10 Research Points should roll on the Amoeba"
" Strength Table. This result will apply to all players, but the player "
"who rolled should not reveal the results to other players until they have"
" completed their own research (they may conduct combat vs Amoebas in "
"secrecy). • The results rolled on the Amoeba Strength Table determine the"
" type for all Amoebas in the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:975
msgid "Amoeba Strength Table"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:977
msgid "Roll Amoeba Type"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:978
msgid "1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:979
msgid "C7-1-1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:980
msgid "2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:981
msgid "D6-2-2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:982
msgid "3"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:983
msgid "A7-2-2. The Amoebas are also vulnerable to fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:984
msgid "4"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:985
msgid "A7-2-2. The Amoebas become an A5-1-2 when faced by ONLY Raiders."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:986
msgid "5"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:987
msgid ""
"B5-1-2. The Amoebas have voracious appetites and gets two attacks each "
"round. Each of these attacks may lead to a Chain Attack ([10.6.3])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:988
msgid "6-7"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:989
msgid ""
"A7-2-2. In any round in which there are 3 or more different types of "
"ships (for example: SC, DD, and CA) attacking the Amoebas, all attacking "
"ships get +1 to their attack."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:990
msgid "8-10"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:991
msgid ""
"The Amoebas can only be killed by detonating a ship inside them. Only one"
" ship may attempt this per turn. If the ship is a CA, BC, BB, DN, or "
"Titan, the Amoeba is destroyed. If the ship is a DD or MB the Amoeba is "
"destroyed on a roll of 1-8 and if the ship is a SC the Amoeba is "
"destroyed on a roll of 1-4. In all cases, the ship attempting this is "
"destroyed. Only the ships listed here can be used. If the Amoeba "
"survives, other ships in the hex with the Amoeba are destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:999
msgid "Explanation of Strength Table Results"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1001
msgid ""
"• On a result of 8-10, no adjustment to weapons will work on the Amoebas "
"and the only way to destroy one is by detonating a ship inside of it. • "
"Any other result means it is now possible to attack them and this is the "
"Amoebas’ Attack-Defense-Hull Size in combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1009
msgid "Amoeba Properties"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1011
msgid ""
"• All Amoebas have a Tactics Level of 2. • All Amoebas are immune to "
"Cloaking and Fighters unless otherwise specified. • Ships never get a "
"Fleet Size Bonus ([MRB 5.1.3]) against Amoebas."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1019
msgid "Amoeba Target Priority"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1021
msgid "Each time an Amoeba attacks,"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1022
msgid ""
"these mindless denizens of the interstellar void roll a die to determine "
"which ship they will attempt to swallow (attack). On a roll of 1-5 it "
"will attack the smallest ship in combat. On a roll of 6-10 it will attack"
" the largest ship in the combat. Use the CP value of a ship to determine "
"largest and smallest. Since Flagships are irreplaceable, they are "
"considered to have the highest CP value. If there is a tie, the player "
"chooses the target of the Space Amoeba. If a player chooses to, they may "
"allow their SVs to be attacked (sometimes useful after the Amoebas have "
"been researched as the SVs have a chance to be destroyed anyway."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1030
msgid "Amoeba Attack Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1032
msgid "The Amoeba rolls one die"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1033
msgid ""
"and executes the attack normally, comparing its Attack Strength to the "
"ship’s Defense Strength (including technology). However, larger ships are"
" even harder to swallow. Ships with a Hull Size of 2 get an extra +1 to "
"their Defense Strength and ships with a Hull Size of 3 (or larger) get an"
" extra +2 to their Defense Strength. A successful attack results in the "
"ship being swallowed (destroyed) regardless of size. As always, a roll of"
" 1 is a successful attack and will swallow a ship, regardless of Defense "
"Strength and size."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1041
msgid "Chain Attacks"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1043
msgid "If an Amoeba successfully swallows a ship,"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1044
msgid ""
"and rolls 2 or less than was needed, then the extra energy gained from "
"swallowing the ship allows the Amoeba to immediately attack again. This "
"can happen any number of times during a round of combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1045
msgid ""
"EXAMPLE: A Type 4 Amoeba (A7-2-2) is being attacked by four Scouts, a "
"Cruiser, and a Battleship. All of the ships have Defense Technology 1. "
"The Amoeba attacks first. It rolls a 3 and so will attack the smallest "
"ship (a Scout). On its attack, it rolls a 4. Since it needed a 6, the "
"Amoeba not only swallows the Scout but gets to attack again. This time it"
" rolls a 6 and will attack the largest ship (the Battleship). The "
"Battleship has a Defense Strength of 5 (Defense of 2 + Defense Tech 1 + 2"
" because of Hull Size 3). The Amoeba rolls a 1, swallowing the "
"Battleship. However, since it was only one less than was needed, it does "
"not get to make a further chain attack."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1053
msgid "Amoeba Healing"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1055
msgid "After combat, damage to an Amoeba"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1056
msgid "is healed in the same way as ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1064
msgid "Spreading Of Space Amoebas"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1066
msgid ""
"Amoebas never move. Once placed, an Amoeba counter never moves to a new "
"hex. Instead, Amoebas spread at the start of the Economic Phase before "
"players make any purchases."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1074
msgid "Spread Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1076
msgid "Amoeba spreading is not random."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1077
msgid ""
"The following guidelines and restrictions apply to the spreading: • Space"
" Amoebas do not start spreading until Economic Phase 7 (or a different "
"phase upon the mutual agreement of all players). • Only one Amoeba may "
"ever be in a hex. • Each Amoeba may only spread one time into one hex "
"during an Economic Phase. • In turn order, each player picks an Amoeba "
"and chooses the hex that it will spread to, placing a new Amoeba in that "
"hex. This process continues until all Amoebas have spread once. • If an "
"Amoeba can spread onto a planet, when selected for spreading, it must "
"spread to the planet hex. If it can spread to multiple planets, the "
"person selecting it can choose which planet hex it spreads to. The "
"presence or absence of a Colony is not a factor. • Newly placed Amoebas "
"do not spread. New Amoebas placed that Economic Phase should be marked in"
" some way so that they are not accidentally selected to spread. • Because"
" Amoebas are attracted to the energy signature of the players’ Empires, "
"they will never spread outside of the map area denoted by the chosen "
"scenario map. • Space Amoebas will not spread into the same hex as a "
"Doomsday Machine and a DM will not move into or through a hex with an "
"Amoeba. • Amoebas are not limited by the number of counters available. "
"Use substitutions when necessary."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1085
msgid "Amoeba Contact with Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1087
msgid "If there are ships in the"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1088
msgid ""
"hex in which an Amoeba spreads, a special combat round occurs immediately"
" during the Economic Phase, with the Amoeba as the attacker. If a player "
"with ships in that hex has not gathered 10 Research Points, all their "
"ships that are not Science Vessels are destroyed (SVs get a Research "
"roll). Space Amoebas automatically destroy neutral Non-Player Alien ships"
" when they spread into their hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1096
msgid "Amoeba Contact with System Markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1098
msgid "An Amoeba"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1099
msgid ""
"removes the System marker or Terrain Tile (MRB 6.10, whether explored or "
"not) in any hex in which it spreads (only after defeating any ships "
"present). If a hex has not been explored, the Amoeba spreads normally and"
" the System marker is removed, sight unseen."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1100
msgid ""
"An Amoeba will not spread into Black Holes ([MRB 6.3]) or Supernovas "
"([MRB 6.5]). Amoebas skip hexes with Folds In Space ([MRB 25.2]) as "
"normal, but in all other cases, Amoebae are totally unaffected by System "
"markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1108
msgid "Space Amoebas And Mines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1110
msgid ""
"Space Amoebas are hindered from spreading by Mines. However, Mines never "
"affect Amoebas like they do ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1118
msgid "Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1120
msgid "If a player moves only a Mine (or a Mine"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1121
msgid ""
"and Science Vessels) into the same hex as an Amoeba, no combat occurs. In"
" the Economic Phase, the Mine is removed, and that Amoeba does not spread"
" during that one Economic Phase. No other harm comes to the Amoeba."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1129
msgid "Contact with Mines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1131
msgid "Amoebas may spread onto Mines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1132
msgid ""
"normally; in which case the Mines have no effect but will remain in the "
"hex until the next Economic Phase when they may stop the Amoeba from "
"spreading as noted above. A Mine only stops an Amoeba from spreading if "
"it is in the same hex as the Amoeba at the start of the Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1140
msgid "Adapting to Mines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1142
msgid "Amoebas will eventually"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1143
msgid ""
"adapt to the use of Mines. Once each Economic Phase an Amoeba does not "
"spread because of any player’s Mine, roll a die. On a result of 9-10, "
"Amoebas will no longer be prevented from spreading by Mines in future "
"Economic Phases. At the conclusion of every Economic Phase, a Mine will "
"be immediately destroyed when occupying a hex with an Amoeba. Place a “No"
" Mine” counter on one of the Amoebas as a reminder that Mines no longer "
"affect them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1151
msgid "2-Player Space Amoebas"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1160
msgid "3-Player Space Amoebas"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1169
msgid "4-Player Space Amoebas"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1178
msgid "Alternate Victory Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1180
msgid ""
"Both of the following alternate victory scenarios can be played in "
"conjunction with almost every scenario in the game. A player still wins "
"by being the first to destroy a Homeworld, but there is also another way "
"to win through Victory Points (VPs). You can’t focus so much on the other"
" way to win that you let your defense go slack."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1181
msgid ""
"Use victory point chips or money from another game or scrap paper to "
"track VPs. Everyone’s total score is always known and is open "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1189
msgid "King Of The Warp Point"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1191
msgid ""
"The Warp Points are the key to victory in this scenario. They represent "
"access to vast scientific treasures and ancient civilizations. By "
"studying them, players unlock knowledge that will lead them to make "
"galaxy changing advances."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1201
msgid "Before the Deep Space markers are placed on"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1202
msgid ""
"the map, the Warp Points ([MRB 28.2]) are taken out of the mix. Depending"
" on the scenario, a number of Warp Points are placed in mutually agreed "
"upon hexes in the Deep Space portion of the map. Some guidelines on Warp "
"Point placement: • It is strongly suggested that you use either: - One "
"Warp Point, or - One less Warp Point than the number of players, or - One"
" more Warp Point than the number of players. • All of the Warp Points can"
" be placed centrally, or one could be placed to the advantage of each "
"player with an extra one in the middle. There are a lot of options, and "
"each will change the game. Design Note: Each of the above will make for a"
" very different and interesting game – is it important to hold one Warp "
"Point or do I need to hold several?"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1203
msgid ""
"If the players cannot agree on the placement of the Warp Points, one "
"player should place all the Warp Points while the other players choose "
"their starting positions once the Warp Points have been placed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1204
msgid ""
"Unused Warp Points should be placed to the side and not mixed in with the"
" rest of the Deep Space Markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1212
msgid "Warp Point Properties"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1214
msgid "None of the Warp Points in this"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1215
msgid "scenario are connected. Their only purpose is to provide VPs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1223
msgid "Minesweepers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1225
msgid "These ships have a dual function in this"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1226
msgid ""
"scenario. They not only sweep Mines, but also act as Science Vessels. You"
" must still research Minesweeping Technology to build SWs ([MRB 17.2])."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1234
msgid "Game Length"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1236
msgid "Players should decide at the start of the"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1237
msgid ""
"game how many Economic Phases they want the game to last. The game ends "
"after that Economic Phase. 10-12 Econ Phases are good for a shorter game,"
" depending on the scenario. This scenario also works with a longer game "
"of 15-20 Econ Phases, although players in that one will have to be "
"careful not to become too focused on the Warp Points as it will become "
"more and more likely that someone will launch a game-winning attack "
"against a Homeworld."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1245
msgid "Victory Points"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1247
msgid "Players score 1 VP during the Economic"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1248
msgid ""
"Phase for each Warp Point that shares a hex with one or more of their "
"Science Vessels. All Science Vessels in the same hex as a Warp Point must"
" be revealed during the Economic Phase. The player with the most VPs at "
"the end of the agreed upon number of Economic Phases is the winner. In "
"the event of a tie, after the purchases for the Economic Phase are "
"completed, the players add up the CP value of all combat-capable ships "
"they have on the board and the winner is the player whose fleet adds up "
"to the most CP. In the event of another tie, the tied players share the "
"win."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1256
msgid "Alternate Point Scoring"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1258
msgid "As a twist to this scenario,"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1259
msgid ""
"players can agree that they will score 1 VP per Science Vessel at a Warp "
"Point in the Economic Phase. This will change the scenario strategy "
"significantly (weighing combat capability versus number of Science "
"Vessels is tough) and it is recommended that this version is played with "
"only one Warp Point."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1267
msgid "Grab The Artifacts"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1269
msgid ""
"Ancient artifacts of great value litter Deep Space and players must "
"gather and study them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1279
msgid "Extra pieces or counters will be needed for this"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1280
msgid ""
"scenario (pieces from an old Risk game will work well). One of these "
"extra pieces is placed in every Deep Space hex (along with the "
"exploration marker). These will represent the ancient artifacts."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1288
msgid "Exploring Artifacts"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1290
msgid "After exploration, artifacts remain"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1291
msgid ""
"in the hex even if the System marker is removed (Danger!, etc.). "
"Exception: Artifacts in Supernovas ([MRB 6.5]), Folds In Space ([MRB "
"25.2]), and Quantum Filaments ([MRB 25.5]) are removed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1299
msgid "Moving Artifacts"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1301
msgid "Artifacts may only be moved by"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1302
msgid ""
"Miners. Place the artifact on the Miner counter when a Miner picks it up."
" They may pick up an artifact at any point during their move. The "
"following rules apply to moving artifacts:"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1303
msgid ""
"• Each Miner may carry only one artifact at a time and may not carry "
"minerals or Space Wrecks at the same time. • Artifacts being towed by "
"Miners are destroyed if the Miner is destroyed. • Miners may drop off "
"artifacts at their Homeworld or at a Colony that is connected by MS "
"Pipelines to the Homeworld (it is assumed a civilian ship is able to "
"transport the artifact from there). Miners may not drop off artifacts at "
"Colonies that are not yet connected in this way."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1313
msgid "Each artifact dropped off is worth"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1314
msgid ""
"1 VP the instant it is dropped off. The game ends immediately (even in "
"the middle of a turn) once someone has scored enough VPs that there is no"
" possible way that their total may be passed by another player given the "
"artifacts remaining on the board. In the event of a tie, the person who "
"achieved their Victory Point total first is declared the winner."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1322
msgid "Taking A Stand"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1324
msgid "(2-Player Variant)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1325
msgid ""
"The following variants add the use of plastic stands which either provide"
" more access to information or add an additional element of hidden "
"information to the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1333
msgid "Standing Ships Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1335
msgid ""
"• Unrevealed ships are not placed face down as in the normal game. "
"Instead, ships are placed upright in stands facing the player. • The "
"number of ships in each group is tracked on the Ship Technology Sheet. • "
"When a group is revealed, it is placed face up and a numeral marker "
"placed underneath. • Groups still have a limit of six ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1343
msgid "2-Player Hidden Exploration"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1345
msgid "VARIANT"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1353
msgid "Changes to Exploration"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1355
msgid ""
"• The map is set up normally, with face down System markers. • Deep Space"
" markers must be explored by both sides. When a Deep Space System marker "
"is explored or would be returned face up with Exploration technology "
"([MRB 9.8]) for the first time, it is not flipped face up and it may not "
"be left face down. Instead, it is placed upright in a stand facing the "
"exploring player. Some markers will be facing one player and some the "
"other, depending on who explored it. If a marker is explored by the other"
" player, it is then removed from the stand and placed face up. All "
"markers that have been explored by both players will be face up on the "
"board. • When a Deep Space System marker is explored by a ship for the "
"first time, a Decoy ([MRB 8.3]) may be added to the hex. Players may "
"scuttle another decoy during the exploration phase to accommodate this. "
"After looking at the System marker and placing it in a stand, the player "
"removes either the Decoy or the exploring ship. There will be one marker "
"left in the hex, but the other player will not know whether it is a Decoy"
" or a ship and therefore will be less likely to know if the Exploration "
"went well. - If the System marker indicates that the hex is safe, the "
"player removes the Decoy. - If the System marker indicates the ship’s "
"destruction, the player removes the ship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1365
#, python-format
msgid ""
"• Deep Space Black Holes ([MRB 6.3]) are 100% deadly until explored by "
"both players. If not face up or in a stand, a Deep Space Black Hole will "
"always suck in the first exploring ship(s) (no need to roll the die). "
"When this occurs, the Decoy marker is left behind. Future ships entering "
"the hex roll the die as normal (which will give"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1366
#, python-format
msgid ""
"away that this is a Black Hole) • Alien planets ([MRB 18.0]) are also "
"100% deadly if attacked by a lone ship. The first time an alien planet is"
" discovered and placed in a stand, it is treated like a Danger! marker "
"and the exploring ship is removed without die rolls (leaving the Decoy "
"marker behind). NPA ships are not chosen and placed in the hex until both"
" sides have explored the planet or it is attacked by more than one ship. "
"• Lost in Space markers ([MRB 6.6]) are treated like Danger! markers when"
" first explored. Future ships from the same player entering the hex later"
" ignore the effect. • Space Pirates ([MRB 25.7]) are turned face up and "
"handled normally. • Regional Maps ([MRB 25.6]) are turned face up and "
"handled normally (which could cause adjacent markers to be put in "
"stands). • Minerals ([MRB 6.7]) and Space Wrecks ([MRB 6.8]) are placed "
"in stands. However, if that player sends a Miner into the hex, it can be "
"removed from the stand and picked up normally. • Supernovas ([MRB 6.5]) "
"are treated like Danger! markers ([MRB 6.4]) when first explored. If "
"explored by a ship, the Decoy is left behind in the hex and must be moved"
" out during the next turn. It is possible that this could cause a Decoy "
"to pass through a Supernova and out the other side under this one "
"exception. The player that has explored the Supernova may not send ships "
"into the hex. • Folds In Space ([MRB 25.2]) have no effect when first "
"explored, remove the Decoy. Future ships may either enter the hex and "
"ignore the usual effects or move through it. Once a ship moves through it"
" remove the marker from the stand and place it face up. • Quantum "
"Filaments ([MRB 25.5]) are treated like Danger! markers when first "
"explored. Future ships from the same player may enter, but must spend an "
"extra movement hex as normal. • Note that a player may ignore beneficial "
"terrain effects (e.g. Pulsars [MRB 25.4]) to keep the terrain tile hidden"
" from their opponent."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1374
msgid "Game Effects"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1376
msgid ""
"• This variant creates paths that can be easily traversed by one player "
"(because they’ve explored it), but not the other. That will at times "
"allow a fleet to more easily retreat or avoid combat. • Both players are "
"more likely to research Exploration technology because they will not be "
"able to easily use a path made by the other player. • The cost of "
"suffering a bad exploration result is slightly less because the player "
"will receive a Decoy as a result. • There will be more Decoys on the "
"board."
msgstr ""

